Security groups.

A security group is a virtual firewall attached to a network interface, on an instance, a load balancer, a database, a function, anything with an address in your network. Four properties shape how you design with them.

It's stateful, so if you allow inbound on a port, the return traffic is allowed automatically and you don't write a matching outbound rule. It has allow rules only; there's no deny, and everything not permitted is implicitly denied. You can attach several to one interface, and their rules combine additively, so if any group allows the traffic, it's allowed. And a rule can reference another security group as its source instead of an address range, which is both more expressive and more maintainable because it tracks instances automatically as they scale.

The canonical pattern is the layered chain: the load-balancer group allows the web port from the internet, the app group allows its port from the load-balancer group, and the database group allows its port from the app group, each layer trusting only the one above it.
